<DOC><DOCNO> AP890111-0096 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1225EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-People-Sadler     01-11 0278</FIRST><SECOND>PM-People-Sadler,0289</SECOND><HEAD>`Green Beret' Singer Barry Sadler Missing, Family Says</HEAD><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Singer-author Barry Sadler, who sufferedbrain damage when he was shot in the head last year in Guatemala, ismissing and needs medical attention, his family says.   Sadler's wife and children said he was discharged Sunday nightfrom a Veterans Administration Hospital in Cleveland, Ohio, and theydon't know where he is now.   Sadler, 48, whose ``Ballad of the Green Berets'' was a No. 1 songin 1966 and who also has written a series of best-selling adventurenovels, was shot in the head during a robbery attempt at his home inGuatemala City in September.   He was brought to a VA hospital in Nashville and transferred tothe hospital in Cleveland in November.   Sadler's wife, Lavona Ruth Sadler, and her children, who live inHendersonville and Murfreesboro, had planned to go to Ohio and flySadler back to the Nashville hospital Monday.   But Mrs. Sadler said the hospital night shift in Clevelandbelieved ``they had to release him because he had not been adjudgedlegally incompetent.''   Hospital spokeswoman Jane Kennedy-Aspis was not immediatelyavailable for comment this morning, her office said.   Mrs. Sadler filed a lawsuit Tuesday seeking to establish aguardianship for her husband, contending he is ``unable to attend tohis business affairs, make rational decisions or control all of hisbodily functions.''   He also has a life-threatening blood clot in his left leg and acatheter that could cause serious infection, the lawsuit said.   Probate Judge Jim Everett appointed Thor Sadler, 24, as hisfather's temporary guardian Tuesday and set a hearing for Jan. 18 ona permanent guardian.</TEXT></DOC>